Clustering (Part I)

Ryan Miller

Unsupervised Learning - Review

  • In supervised learning we use a set of features, \(\mathbf{X} = \{X_1,X_2,\ldots,X_p\}\), to model or predict an outcome variable \(Y\)
  • In unsupervised learning we have \(\mathbf{X} = \{X_1,X_2,\ldots,X_p\}\), but no natural outcome variable to model, instead the goal is to find hidden patterns or groups within the data

Clustering vs.PCA

  • Principal component analysis (PCA) is a tool used to discover hidden relationships among the variables (columns) of a dataset
    • PCA might suggest certain groups of variables might represent a single latent factor
  • Clustering focuses on the data-points themselves (rows), suggesting that observations might be members of latent groups
  • There are many types of clustering, we will focus on two broad categories:
    • Partitional Clustering: divides the data-points into non-overlapping subsets
    • Hierarchical Clustering: organizes the data-points into a nested subsets

Image Source: Quantdare

Clustering - A Simple Example

  • The plot below provides a simple illustration of partitional clustering done on the USArrests dataset
    • States are grouped into non-overlapping subsets (red vs.blue) based upon their urban population and murder rate
  • Cluster membership is estimated from the data
    • How might we determine if a certain state (say Virginia) is a better fit in Cluster #1 or Cluster #2?

Measuring Distance

  • Good clusters should contain data-points that are similar (close to) each other, and dissimilar (far from) from data-points in other clusters

  • To objectively measure closeness we need to define a distance metric, the simplest choice is Euclidean distance: \[d_{a,b} = \sqrt{\sum_{j = 1}^{p} (x_{aj} - x_{bj})^2}\]

  • The Euclidean distance between two data-points, \(x_a\) and \(x_b\), is defined as the sum of the squared differences in their values across each variable (we index these variables by \(j \in \{1, \ldots, p\}\))

Distance Matrices

  • For data with \(n\) observations, we can construct an \(n\)-by-\(n\) matrix of the distances between each pair of data-points
  • By visualizing the distance matrix we can discover trends in the data:
USA2 <- select(USArrests, "UrbanPop", "Murder")
distance <- get_dist(USA2)
fviz_dist(distance)

Standardization

  • As was the case with PCA, the units of each variable can lead certain variables to disproportionately influence distance calculations
    • Because of this, we might consider standardization (re-scaling) the data
  • We can see the impact this has on the USArrests data:

  • In the distance matrix of the unstandardized data, the variable UrbanPop is dominating the distance calculation. Standardizing the data (using the scale function) leads to more balanced results

Prototype-based Clustering

  • So far weve established
    • Good clusters should contain data-points that are close to each other and are far from data-points in other clusters
    • Closeness can be measured via Euclidean distance
  • One approach to translating these two ideas into clusters is to introduce **prototypes*, or entities that define each cluster
    • For most applications, a prototype can be thought of as a central point representing a particular cluster
    • Prototypes may be an abstraction of the data (ie: the centroid or multi-dimensional mean), or a data-point itself (ie: the medoid or multi-dimensional median)

Image source: Applied Unsupervised Learning with R

\(k\)-means Clustering

  • k-means clustering is a prototype-based partitional clustering method

  • Let \(\mu_k\) denote the centroid of \(C_k\), the \(k^{th}\) cluster, and let \(x_i\) be the \(i^{th}\) data-point in the \(k^{th}\) cluster, then: \[\text{Total Withiness} = \sum_{k=1}^{k} W(C_k) = \sum_{k=1}^{k} \sum_{x_i \in C_k} (x_i - \mu_k)^2 \]

  • For a fixed \(k\), the optimal cluster assignment minimizes Total Withiness (sometimes called the total within cluster sum of squares), this assignment defines the \(k\)-means clusters

\(k\)-Means Clustering - Algorithm

  1. Initialize \(k\) centroids (typically at random)
  2. Calculate the distance from each data-point to each centroid
  3. Assign data-points to the nearest centroid (defined by minimum distance)
  4. Update the cluster centroids (using the mean of the assigned data-points)
  5. Repeat (2) - (4) until there is no change

Image source: Wikimedia

Visualizing \(k\)-Means

  • In many applications clustering is combined with PCA in order to provide effective low-dimensional visualizations
  • For the USArrests data, recall that PC1 roughly represented overall crime, and PC2 roughly represented urban population
    • Applying \(k\)-means (with \(k = 2\)), states are mostly grouping according to their crime rates
    • This is not unexpected, most of the variation in the USArrests dataset exists in the overall crime dimension

Choosing \(k\)

  • Dozens of methods have been proposed for determining the optimal number of clusters (\(k\)), we will discuss three of them:
    • The elbow method
    • The silhouette method
    • The gap statistic

The Elbow Method

  • The elbow method is simple and intuitive, it requires us to plot Total Withiness or wss versus the number of clusters and look for an elbow
    • By definition, wss will always decrease with \(k\), but eventually these decreases become small
    • The elbow occurs where minimal improvement is seen when further increasing \(k\)
    • For the USArrests dataset, 2-4 clusters seems reasonable
## Standardize the data
USArrests_scaled <- scale(USArrests)

## Plot for the Elbow Method
fviz_nbclust(USArrests_scaled, kmeans, method = "wss", k.max = 8)

The Silhouette Method

  • The elbow method is somewhat subjective, whereas the silhouette method objectively calculates the silhouette value of each data-point
  • In the silhouette method, a silhouette is calculated each data-point using the following steps:
  1. For data-point \(x_i\) belonging to cluster \(C_k\), calculate the average distance to all other members of \(C_k\), then call this value \(a_i\)
  2. For each cluster not containing \(x_i\), calculate the average distance between \(x_i\) and the members of that cluster, then call the minimum of these distances \(b_i\)
  3. Define the silhouette for \(x_i\) as \(s_i = (b_i - a_i)/max(a_i,b_i)\)
  • Silhouettes can range from -1 (a poor fit within the assigned cluster) to +1 (an excellent fit within the assigned cluster)
  • Negative silhouettes are undesirable, they indicate a data-point is actually closer to the data-points in another cluster

The Silhouette Method

  • The average silhouette value can be used to determine the optimal \(k\)
  • In the USArrests example, the method suggests \(k = 2\) is optimal

The Silhouette Method

  • Silhouettes are also useful to investigate how well individual data-points fit within their assigned cluster
##   cluster size ave.sil.width
## 1       1   20          0.37
## 2       2   30          0.43

The Gap Statistic

  • As previously mentioned, Total Withiness always declines as \(k\) increases
  • The idea behind the gap statistic is to determine the expected wss for a given \(k\), then look at the gap between the expected and observed wss
    • More specific details can be found in this paper
  • Note that larger gap statistics are desirable, as they indicate the clusters are doing better than expected
  • When using the gap statistic we should also consider the simple-to-complex principle
    • By default, fviz_nbclust will select the smallest \(k\) within one standard error of the maximum

  • All of the results and examples in this presentation have used Euclidean distance, but many other distance measures exist, each with their own strengths and weaknesses
